# Convert mpg to km/l (1 mpg = 1.6 km/g = 0.42 km / l) and compute avg mpg & km/l by cylinder

mtcars %>%

  group_by(cyl) %>% 
  summarize(avg_US = mean(mpg), avg_metric = mean(kml))

Some possibly useful material

  1. Each of the verbs mutate, arrange, filter and summarize have scoped versions: *_all. *_at and *_if.

    The variants suffixed with _if, _at or _all apply an expression (sometimes several) to all variables within a specified subset. This subset can contain all variables (_all variants), a vars() selection (_at variants), or variables selected with a predicate (_if variants).

  2. You should create your own theme for all of the plots in this assignment. The way you do this is using the following template (take out or add in elements):

library(extrafont)
# extrafont::import_fonts() # Loads system fonts
my_theme <- function(){
  theme_bw() + 
    theme(axis.title = element_text(size = 14, family='Roboto'),
          axis.text = element_text(size = 12, family='Roboto'))
}

Look at the documentation for theme (using ?theme) . There are nice descriptions here and here. You can also choose something from the ggthemes package (which you may need to install).

  1. We already saw that there are only 2 years in this dataset. So it will be useful to convert this into a factor, which is a type meant for categorical data. Weâll do it in place, i.e., change the original data rather than make a copy.
mpg <- mpg %>% 
  mutate(year = as.factor(year)) #reminder, we are changing a variable
  1. Letâs change all the character variables to factors too.
mpg <- mpg %>% 
  mutate_if(is.character, as.factor) #if a column is a character, change to a factor
  1. Create a new dataset from mpg, where all the efficiencies are in one column, and another column denotes whether the data comes from city or highway mileage. Weâll need these for some graphics later.
mpg1 <- mpg %>% 
  gather(location, mileage, cty, hwy)

Question 6

Show the relationship between displacement (displ) and fuel efficiency in one plot. This should be a scatter plot with a smooth line, with colors representing city and highway. Make sure the levels in the legend are âcityâ and âhighwayâ rather than âctyâ and âhwyâ. Youâll have to modify the data to do this. One way is suggested below.

Hint: This uses what I called one of my favorite or most used tricks in data manipulation.

## Your code here. Naming choices for 1 and 2 are yours

mpg2<- mpg %>% 
  pivot_longer(c(cty, hwy), names_to = "location", values_to = "mileage") %>%  # Both of those are fill-in-the-blank
  mutate(location = ifelse(location == 'cty', 'city','highway'))

ggplot(mpg2, aes(x = displ, y = mileage)) + 
  geom_point(aes(color = location))  +
  geom_smooth(aes(color = location), se = F)
